# Two Pointers in Java

The two-pointer technique places two index variables into an array or string and moves them strategically — usually toward each other or in the same direction — to avoid a nested O(n²) loop. The core insight: **sorted order or a known invariant lets you decide which pointer to move without trying all combinations**.

## Pattern 1 — Converging pointers on a sorted array
```java
// Picture two people walking toward each other from opposite ends.
// If their sum is too small → left person steps right (increases sum).
// If their sum is too large → right person steps left (decreases sum).
// They meet exactly when no valid pair remains.
//
// Two Sum (sorted array):
int[] twoSum(int[] nums, int target) {
    int l = 0, r = nums.length - 1;
    while (l < r) {
        int sum = nums[l] + nums[r];
        if      (sum == target) return new int[]{l, r};
        else if (sum < target)  l++;  // need bigger sum → advance left
        else                    r--;  // need smaller sum → retreat right
    }
    return new int[]{-1, -1};  // no pair found
}
// Time: O(n)   Space: O(1)  (vs O(n²) brute force)
```

## Pattern 2 — Same-direction pointers (fast/slow)
```java
// One pointer (fast) races ahead finding 'useful' elements;
// the other (slow) marks where the next useful element should be placed.
//
// Remove duplicates from sorted array in-place:
// slow = last position of deduplicated region
// fast = scanner looking for new unique values
//
// [1, 1, 2, 3, 3, 4]
//  s                        slow=0
//     f                     nums[f]=1 == nums[s] → skip
//        f                  nums[f]=2 != nums[s] → place at ++slow
// [1, 2, 2, 3, 3, 4] (slow=1, continue...)
int removeDuplicates(int[] nums) {
    int slow = 0;
    for (int fast = 1; fast < nums.length; fast++)
        if (nums[fast] != nums[slow]) nums[++slow] = nums[fast];
    return slow + 1;  // new length
}
```

## Pattern 3 — Dutch National Flag (3-way partition)
```java
// Sort an array of 0s, 1s, and 2s in O(n) time O(1) space.
//
// Three regions maintained at every step:
//  [0...low-1]   all 0s  (confirmed)
//  [low...mid-1] all 1s  (confirmed)
//  [mid...high]  unknown (unsorted territory)
//  [high+1...n-1] all 2s  (confirmed)
//
// Visual: three hands squeezing inward until mid > high.
//
void sortColors(int[] nums) {
    int low = 0, mid = 0, high = nums.length - 1;
    while (mid <= high) {
        if      (nums[mid] == 0) swap(nums, low++, mid++);  // 0: expand left zone
        else if (nums[mid] == 1) mid++;                     // 1: already in place
        else                     swap(nums, mid, high--);   // 2: send to right zone
        // Note: mid does NOT increment after swapping with high —
        // the swapped element hasn't been examined yet!
    }
}
```

## Pattern 4 — Three Sum (sorted + converging inner pair)
```java
// Fix one element, then use converging two-pointer on the rest.
// Sort first so duplicates are adjacent — easy to skip.
//
List<List<Integer>> threeSum(int[] nums) {
    Arrays.sort(nums);
    List<List<Integer>> res = new ArrayList<>();
    for (int i = 0; i < nums.length - 2; i++) {
        if (i > 0 && nums[i] == nums[i-1]) continue;  // skip duplicate anchor
        int l = i + 1, r = nums.length - 1;
        while (l < r) {
            int sum = nums[i] + nums[l] + nums[r];
            if      (sum == 0) {
                res.add(Arrays.asList(nums[i], nums[l++], nums[r--]));
                while (l < r && nums[l] == nums[l-1]) l++;  // skip duplicates
                while (l < r && nums[r] == nums[r+1]) r--;  // skip duplicates
            }
            else if (sum < 0) l++;
            else              r--;
        }
    }
    return res;
}
```

## Pattern 5 — Merging sorted intervals
```java
// Sort by start. Walk with one pointer, merging overlapping intervals.
//
// [1,3],[2,6],[8,10],[15,18]
//  └──merge──┘ → [1,6]
//              [8,10] no overlap → keep
//                     [15,18] no overlap → keep
//
int[][] merge(int[][] intervals) {
    Arrays.sort(intervals, Comparator.comparingInt(a -> a[0]));
    List<int[]> merged = new ArrayList<>();
    for (int[] cur : intervals) {
        if (merged.isEmpty() || merged.get(merged.size()-1)[1] < cur[0])
            merged.add(cur);   // no overlap — add as new interval
        else
            merged.get(merged.size()-1)[1] = Math.max(merged.get(merged.size()-1)[1], cur[1]);
    }
    return merged.toArray(new int[0][]);
}
```

## Common Pitfalls
- Using converging two-pointer on an UNSORTED array — the sorted invariant is what makes the decision (advance l or retreat r) correct
- Dutch National Flag: incrementing mid after swapping with high — the incoming element from high is unseen and could be anything
- Three Sum: forgetting to skip duplicate anchor values at index i — produces duplicate triplets
- Two Sum: the classic two-pointer only works for finding ONE pair; for ALL pairs use a loop with duplicate-skipping
- Palindrome check: off-by-one — loop must be l < r not l <= r (single middle character is always a palindrome)

## Connections
- **Sorting**: converging two-pointer and interval merging require sorted input
- **Arrays**: all patterns operate in-place with O(1) extra space
- **Sliding Window**: sliding window IS two-pointer (same-direction) but with window state tracking
- **Linked Lists**: fast/slow pointer on a linked list detects cycles and finds the middle

